With this, one query (e.g. `user.id = "user_456"` or `error.code = "card_declined"`) gives the full picture: premium user, 3rd attempt, insufficient funds, new checkout flow — no second search.

## Misconceptions (from the reference)

- **“Structured logging = wide events”** — No. Structured = JSON/table stakes. Wide events = one comprehensive event per request with high cardinality and dimensionality.
- **“We use OTel, so we’re good”** — OTel is transport; you still add business context and a wide-event shape.
- **“This is just tracing”** — Tracing shows flow across services; wide events give context *within* a service. Complementary; ideally the wide event backs or equals the span enriched with context.
- **“High cardinality is too expensive”** — Legacy log search systems struggle; columnar stores (ClickHouse, BigQuery, etc.) are built for high-cardinality, high-dimensionality data.

## What to avoid

- Many log lines per request (prefer one wide event per request per service).
- Plain string-only messages; use structured fields with stable keys.
- Low context (no user/business identifiers) so debugging stays grep archaeology.
- Assuming OpenTelemetry replaces the need to design what to capture.
